entry.content:
Previously, when `SetIsDefault()` was called, the

LabelButton::UpdateStyleToIndicateDefaultStatus was triggered, which

updated the label font to a font list that is not compatible with

cros-next.



This commit overrides the `UpdateStyleToIndicateDefaultStatus` method in

`PillButton` to avoid updating the label font when `SetIsDefault()` is

called, considering `PillButton` already has all the information it

needs to render itself properly with the `type_` value.

entry.title: [dPWA] Add DedupeInstallUrlsCommand
entry.content:
This CL adds a DedupeInstallUrlsCommand that runs at the end of

every ExternallyManagedAppManager::SynchronizeInstalledApps().



This command deals with the scenario where multiple install sources

install the same install URL and end up with conflicting app

installations, e.g. policy installing a placeholder and preinstall

installing an offline manifest.



This deduping step serves as a post install clean up as well as

a fix job for users affected by https://crbug.com/1427340 that

ended up with placeholder-like apps along side full app installs.



Some users ended up in a state where policy installed placeholder

apps became placeholder-like default apps, PreinstalledWebAppManager

has been updated to force_reinstall default apps that look like

placeholders to fix these users.



Once all affected users are fixed up we should consider updating

our install flow to not get into this state to begin with.

For now the clean up logic sufficiently covers both new and

existing duplicate install URLs without needing a rewrite of

how external web app installs work.



Design-Doc: go/sticky-placeholder-web-apps

closed) the promise to resolve the display root terminates with

rejection. This rejection is not handled in any way in the directory

tree. Which means that it propagates to the top of the stack and is

reported by crash site. In M114 this contributes to over 20% of all

crashes.

entry.title: Change ShowSingletonTab* API
entry.content:
This is in preparation for making ShowSingletonTab and ShowSingletonTabOverwritingNTP behave in a Lacros-compatible way

(see the followup-CL).



- Replace all but one use of

ShowSingletonTabOverwritingNTP(Browser*, NavigateParams*)

by uses of

ShowSingletonTabOverwritingNTP(Browser*, const GURL&). These uses

only care about browser and URL.

This change is done because we can't support arbitrary

NavigateParams* for Lacros.

The remaining call where NavigateParams are passed to

ShowSingletonTabOverwritingNTP is in Navigate() and is expected to

be impossible to trigger when Lacros is enabled (unless a developer

opens a tabbed Ash browser for debugging, in which case it would be

okay to open an Ash window).



- Provide a ShowSingletonTab and ShowSingletonTabOverwritingNTP overload

that takes a Profile* instead of a Browser*, so that the potential

creation of a new browser window is encapsulated.



There is no change in behavior for existing code in this CL.



Cleanups:



- Remove dead function chrome::ShowPolicy.

- Remove dead function NetworkPortalSigninController::ShowSingletonTab.

entry.content:
This CL is fixing the broken metric Shutdown.EndSession.Time2.

It is currently not emitted.



The EndSession is a special case in the sense that ChromeDelegate is

not destroyed. The destructor is not called which is where the

metric is recorded [1].



The old metric Shutdown.EndSession.Time is written to prefs here [2]

and is reported at the next browser startup.



To ensure that the metric is recorded, a call to

browser_shutdown::RecordShutdownMetrics() is needed.



NOTE: A follow-up of this CL is to deprecate and delete the V1 of the

shutdown metrics.

entry.title: [BRP/clang-plugin] Adjust file-based exclusion conditions
entry.content:
The following changes will apply

if option `raw-ptr-fix-crbug-1449812` is enabled.

For more details, take a look at crbug.com/1449812



1. File is looked up through SourceLocation obtained via `getLocation()`

Given a fieldDecl below,

```

VOID* field;

^ ^

X Y

```



`fieldDecl.getBeginLoc()` will return position X and

`fieldDecl.getLocation()` or `fieldDecl.getEndLoc()` return position Y.

If we try to get spelling location for X, we will get a file name

where macro `VOID` is defined.

Especially in variable declaration, beginning location is more likely

to be affected from macro.

It would be more accurate to get a file name from `getLocation()`.



2. System header check is based on spelling location

We were using clang's `isExpansionInSystemHeader()`, which is

expansion-location-based.

However, having non-system expansion location not necessarily means

user has control over that decl node.



e.g.



systemheader.h

```

#define INTP_FIELD() int* macro_ptr

```



user.cpp

```

struct MyStruct {

INTP_FIELD();

};

```



In this case,

- `isExpansionInSystemHeader()` returns false.

- `isSpellingInSystemHeader()` returns true.



System header check is switched to use `isSpellingInSystemHeader()`

to ensure users are warned only if they have control.



Bug: 1449812

entry.title: Don't pessimistically abort animations in ScrollIntoView
entry.content:
ScrollIntoView brings a target into view by scrolling all its ancestor

scrollers. It does this by walking up the layout tree, determining how

to scroll each encountered scroller, and queueing the scroll in the

local root frame's SmoothScrollSequencer (despite the name, the

sequencer may also handle instant scrolls). Once all the scrolls are

queued the sequence is begun. Each scroll in the sequence is started

when the previous one ends. For smooth scrolls this plays the animations

sequentially.



In order to prevent having multiple concurrent scroll animations,

ScrollIntoView aborts any existing sequences. However, it does so

pessimistically before performing the queueing procedure. This means

that a no-op ScrollIntoView will cancel an existing scroll sequence.



In the linked bug, the animated scroll is being canceled because the

page puts focus on a visible button (that's position: fixed), causing it

to attempt a superfluous ScrollIntoView.



This CL replaces the single-per-LocalRoot SmoothScrollSequencer with a

new SmoothScrollSequencer for each sequenced operation. After performing

queueing, if the new sequence is empty, the old sequence is replaced to

allow it to continue any in progress (animated) scrolls.

entry.title: Fix test expectations for spacing-style related tests
entry.content:
According to fillText function in CanvasRenderingContext2d, the text

needs to process through text preparation algorithm,

https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#text-preparation-algorithm, where it

states that 'white-space' is set to "pre". According to the CSS

definition of "pre", spaces and tabs are preserved in the line and at

the end of the line. ref:

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-text/#white-space-property



The tests are used to expect the spaces and tabs are collapsed in the

middle of the line and removed at the of the line. This follows

expectation of 'white-space = normal'.



In this cl, I fixed the test expectations. They are now follow

'white-space = pre'.

entry.title: Reland "Integrate text fragments with Document lifecycle"
entry.content:
Reland Note: The "script-running actions" task used a Persistent which

kept the Document alive to the leak detector. There's no reason to keep

this task if the Document is destroyed so the reland makes this a

WeakPersistent. See diff from first PatchSet for updates to originally

landed CL.



This CL is a refactoring to improve how text fragments are integrated

with the document lifecycle. There are several high-level changes here:



- Annotations (the thing that performs text search and applies the

highlights) no longer allow attaching at arbitrary points. Instead,

clients can set an annotation as "needing attachment" and schedule a

BeginFrame. In the next BeginFrame, all annotations needing attachment

perform their search after layout is updated.

- Text fragments have a special case for when a page has never been

visible; the text search is deferred until the page becomes visible.

The above change required moving this behavior into

AnnotationAgentContainerImpl.

- TextFragmentAnchor is no longer responsible for controlling when

annotation attachment occurs. Instead, it's invoked right after

annotations are attached and checks the status of its annotations to

update its internal state and perform scroll into view and related

actions.

- Simplify TextFragmentAnchor's state machine by removing the

ScriptableActions state. Instead, the script-running actions are

scheduled for an animation frame and then move the anchor into the

kDone state.



See also the related followup which this CL enables:

https://crrev.com/c/4586061

entry.title: [relaunch_notification] Fix incorrect deadline in UX
entry.content:
The deadline to force a restart can be revised after an initial

notification is shown in certain situations. The wrong value could be

used for the dialog title in situations such as:



- The user is shown the dialog and dismisses it.

- All browser windows are deactivated.

- Something happens to change the deadline (e.g., the notification

period policy is changed).

- A browser window is activated.



This CL contains two fixes that could contribute to this bad user

experience:



1. The cached deadline is unconditionally updated. This will prevent a

stale deadline from being used.

2. UpgradeDetector no longer clears the deltas for the annoyance level

once the highest level is reached. This could cause its

GetAnnoyanceLevelDeadline method to return zeros.



Also in this CL:



- A DCHECK for negative deltas is added to the dialog title computation

so that we can (hopefully) spot if this happens via other means in the

wild.

- RelaunchNotificationControllerUiTest.ReactivateAfterDeadline is added

as a regression test for this bug.

- The platform_impl_ member of the RelaunchNotificationController class

is moved to the proper location the class decl according to style.

- Some questionable uses of Time in tests have been fixed.
